strip/false/crop/4828x2716+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe5%2Fd5%2F598bda69454bafbf5e6e1729b636%2Fwnba.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4828x2716+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe5%2Fd5%2F598bda69454bafbf5e6e1729b636%2Fwnba.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4828x2716+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe5%2Fd5%2F598bda69454bafbf5e6e1729b636%2Fwnba.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4828x2716+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe5%2Fd5%2F598bda69454bafbf5e6e1729b636%2Fwnba.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4828x2716+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe5%2Fd5%2F598bda69454bafbf5e6e1729b636%2Fwnba.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4828x2716+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe5%2Fd5%2F598bda69454bafbf5e6e1729b636%2Fwnba.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4828x2716+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe5%2Fd5%2F598bda69454bafbf5e6e1729b636%2Fwnba.jpg" class="img" alt="Golden State Valkyries guard Kate Martin (20) struggles to maintain possession against Seattle Storm forward Ezi Magbegor (left) as Valkyries center Temi Fagbenle (14) reaches for the ball during the second half of a WNBA game Wednesday in Seattle. The Valkyries debuted this season as the league&amp;#039;s 13th team." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Golden State Valkyries guard Kate Martin (20) struggles to maintain possession against Seattle Storm forward Ezi Magbegor (left) as Valkyries center Temi Fagbenle (14) reaches for the ball during the second half of a WNBA game Wednesday in Seattle. The Valkyries debuted this season as the league's 13th team.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Lindsey Wasson/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The WNBA is halfway through the 2025 season and is experiencing significant success. TV ratings are up 23% across the board and games are drawing in 13% more fans compared to last year. Total ticket sales are up 26% overall with the debut of the league's 13th team, the Golden State Valkyries. The league is building on its momentum with a plan to expand to 18 teams by 2030. Players are also seeking their own share of the success by pushing for a new contract to address the ongoing issue of low pay. Here's a &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/07/19/nx-s1-5471422/wnba-all-star-game-caitlyn-clark-indianapolis" target="_blank"&gt;breakdown of what is happening&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🏀 Merchandise sales and social media engagement are up. The league will also have a record $2.2 billion media rights deal starting next season, the largest in women's sports history.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🏀 The collective bargaining agreement between owners and players will expire at the end of October. Key issues for players include salaries, revenue sharing, and "prioritization," which allows them to play in other leagues for additional income.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🏀 The league aims to increase revenue by adding more games to the schedule. This year, each team will play 44 regular season games, and the Finals have been extended from a five-game series to a seven-game series. However, the league's traditional calendar — structured to avoid overlap with the NBA — has not changed, meaning more games are expected to be played each week than before.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-43400" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5163;         --source-height: 3407;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5163x3407+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ffa%2Fa8%2Fab4ae109410e9d362134a3fa7ad8%2Fgettyimages-176910681.jpg" class="img" alt="U.S. civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., waves to supporters on August 28, 1963, on the National Mall in Washington D.C." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 U.S. civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., waves to supporters on August 28, 1963, on the National Mall in Washington D.C.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          AFP/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ol class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;The National Archives &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/07/21/nx-s1-5475234/martin-luther-king-jr-records" target="_blank"&gt;released thousands of newly digitized documents&lt;/a&gt; yesterday related to the 1968 assassination of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., as part of an executive order by Trump.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;As the 2025-2026 school year nears, NPR wants to hear from you about the books you read in high school that helped shape who you are today. &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/07/21/nx-s1-5468460/books-that-shaped-you" target="_blank"&gt;Your response could be included&lt;/a&gt; in a list of reader recommendations.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Actor and Grammy Award winner Malcolm-Jamal Warner, best known for his role as Theo Huxtable on &lt;em&gt;The Cosby Show&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/07/21/nx-s1-5475181/malcolm-jamal-warner-dead" target="_blank"&gt;died on Sunday&lt;/a&gt; at age 54.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This newsletter was edited by &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/people/g-s1-2467/obed-manuel"target="_blank"   &gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Obed Manuel&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
